1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 {[#] Hi everyone! Welcome to
the starting position of this repertoire, one of the most ambitious possible
setups against the solid Catalan. With his last move Black aims to create a
pawn chain, securing the extra pawn on c4. Considering the huge amount of
games played at the top level in the last couple of months this variation
might be a serious contender replacing the Old Main Line. It does, in my
opinion, indeed lead to a much more adventurous position than the current Main
Line of the Catalan, reached after 4...Be7 5.Bg2 0-0 6.0-0 dxc4. One little
warning, or rather see it as an encouraging message, particularly the Main
Lines after 4...dxc4 5.Bg2 a6, covered in the last chapters contain incredibly
deep, computer-assisted analysis. I imagine this isn't everyone's cup of tea,
but there are some big advantages compared to the solid variations dealing
with the Catalan. 1) We aren't playing this system to equalize, but rather try
to put White under pressure by sticking to our extra pawn. We are looking for
our own chances! Most of the Chapters offer imbalanced pawn structures or
material distribution, offering good practical chances to play for a win, once
we leave the theoretical territory. Unfortunately, like in most other openings,
there are some dull lines or even forcing sequences leading to a draw, but
don't get discouraged by that. Most of the time while analyzing, I was
thrilled by the fascinating lines I came across. 2) The real good news is that
you don't have to make these analyses yourself. I have done it for you, and
yes, it took me a lot of time. I'm not complaining, to the contrary, I'm
feeling proud of this work and ready to accept the challenge facing any
Catalans in the near future! I hope you like it as much as I do. Let's start
with White's minor alternatives on move 6.} 6. a4 (6. Nc3 b5 (6... Nc6 $6 {
doesn't really appeal to me, in view of} 7. Qa4 $1 (7. O-O Rb8 {would actually
transpose to positions examined in Chapter 6.}) 7... b5 8. Nxb5 Bd7 9. Na3 Nxd4
10. Qxc4 Bc6 (10... Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Rb8 12. O-O $16 {Le-Wang Hao, Beijing 2008.}
) 11. O-O Nxf3+ {and this position was reached in two correspondence games,
which both ended in a draw, but still, I feel White is still somewhat better
after either recapture.}) 7. Ne5 (7. a4 b4 8. Ne5 (8. Nb1 $6 Bb7 9. O-O c5 10.
Qc2 {was played in Sokolov-Nikolic, Sarajevo 1987 and now} (10. Nbd2 {is
perhaps better, but White is struggling to equalize.}) 10... Nc6 11. Qxc4 Na5 {
is already quite bad for White.}) 8... Ra7 ({After} 8... bxc3 $5 9. Bxa8 cxb2
10. Bxb2 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 c3 $44 {Black seems to obtain sufficient compensation
for the exchange.}) 9. Ne4 Nxe4 (9... Bb7 $5 10. f3 (10. Nxf6+ $2 gxf6 $1 $17)
10... Bd5 {, planning a quick ... c7-c5, might be an interesting idea to fight
for the initiative.}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Rxb7 12. O-O Qd5 13. Bf4 Bd6 $132 (
13... Nc6 $2 14. e4 Qxe4 15. Re1 Qd5 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. d5 $18 {Akobian-Greet,
Gibraltar 2008.})) 7... Ra7 $5 (7... c6 {transposes to a well-known position
from the Semi-Slav/Catalan systems.}) 8. O-O (8. Bc6+ Bd7 {is absolutely fine.}
) (8. a4 Bb7 9. Bxb7 Rxb7 10. axb5 axb5 11. O-O {was seen in Wang Yue-Jianu,
Bazna 2014, but now after} Be7 {I fail to see an effective plan for White to
prove sufficient play for the pawn.}) 8... Bb7 9. e4 Nbd7 {and compared to
Slav structures, I like that Black hasn't placed a pawn on c6. The diagonal
for the bishop on b7 is open and Black retains the option to play ...c7-c5 in
one go.}) (6. Nbd2 {is pretty senseless too, e.g.} b5 7. Ne5 Nd5 (7... Qxd4 $5)
8. O-O Bb7 {just looks better for Black.}) (6. Qc2 $6 {the queen is vulnerable
on this square as it easily comes under threat by one of Black's knights.} b5
7. Ne5 (7. a4 Bb7 8. axb5 (8. b3 $2 {is met by} Nc6 $1 9. bxc4 Nxd4 10. Qb2
Nxf3+ 11. exf3 b4 {and Black is winning in Tsiganova-Zatonskih, Tromsoe 2014.})
8... axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 10. Nc3 b4 11. Nd1 Bd5 $17 {and White doesn't have
sufficient compensation for the pawn in Maslik-Banusz, Austria 2017.}) 7... Nd5
8. O-O Bb7 9. e4 (9. Bd2 Nd7 (9... c5 $5 {is also good.}) 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Rd1
f5 12. e4 Nf6 13. Nc3 b4 14. Ne2 Nxe4 15. Qxc4 Bd5 $17 {Monjardin Cruz-Bruzon
Batista, Merida 2007.}) (9. a4 {was seen in Zambo-Banusz, Szombathely 2010,
but now} Nb4 10. Qd1 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 N8c6 {is just a healthy extra pawn for
Black.}) 9... Nb4 $1 10. Qd1 (10. Qe2 Qxd4 (10... Nd7 $5 {is the easiest way
to claim a significant plus.}) 11. Be3 Qxe5 12. f4 Qd6 13. e5 Qd3 14. Qxd3 {
was seen in Van Harreveld-De Roda Husman, Netherlands 2001, where Black took
on g2, but simpler and better is} cxd3 $1 15. Bxb7 Nc2 16. Bf2 Nxa1 17. Bxa8
Nc2 {and Black is on top.} (17... c5 $6 18. Na3 $1)) 10... Nd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7
12. Be3 c5 $19 {and White's position falls apart in Fuchs-Schlosser, Baden
2019.}) (6. Qa4+ $2 b5 {is not an option.}) 6... Nc6 7. O-O Rb8 {leads to a
position covered in Chapter 3.} *

