-15,-13,-13,-10,-12,-10,-10,-18,-13,-9]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3
dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. Ne5 {The most straightforward try for White, as he is about
recapturing the pawn on c4 and doesn't give Black a chance to protect it with .
..b7-b5.} Bb4+ ({The main alternative here is} 6... c5 {which was played twice
by Topalov in his World Championship match with Anand in 2010.}) 7. Nc3 ({
The gambit line} 7. Bd2 $6 {has been seen in a couple times, but isn't very
promising:} Qxd4 8. Bxb4 (8. Qa4+ Nbd7 9. Qxb4 Qxe5 10. Nc3 Qc5 $15 {
Kanep-Vitiugov, Tallinn 2006.}) 8... Qxe5 9. Na3 (9. Nd2 Qb5 10. Ba3 Bd7 {
followed by ...Bc6 and Black is perfectly fine in Kamsky-Wang Hao, Tashkent
2012.}) 9... Nc6 $1 {Compared with the Open Catalan with ...c7-c6 instead of ..
.a7-a6 Black doesn't have this resource.} 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Bc3 Qd5 12. f3 e5
$1 {with comfortable play as the light-squared bishop will get out.} 13. e4 $6
Qc5 14. Qd2 Be6 $17 {Aronian-Mamedyarov, Ohrid 2009.}) 7... Nd5 8. O-O ({
Playing in gambit style is obviously the most ambitious continuation. After} 8.
Bd2 Nb6 $1 {Black's position turns out to be very solid.} ({In my opinion more
reliable than} 8... b5 $6 {which is a better practical attempt to play for a
win, but involves some strategical risk.} 9. O-O Bxc3 (9... Bb7 $2 10. Nxd5 $1
Bxd2 11. Nf6+ gxf6 12. Bxb7 fxe5 13. Bxa8 Qxd4 14. Qc2 $16 {Fridman-Caspi,
Israel 2019.}) 10. bxc3 O-O (10... f6 $2 11. e4 Ne7 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Nxg6 Nxg6
14. f4 {and White is winning in Kopylov-Solleveld, Germany 2009.}) 11. a4 ({
Less accurate is} 11. e4 $6 Nb6 $1 12. f4 Bb7 13. f5 exf5 14. Rxf5 N8d7 15. Ng4
Qe7 {with a reasonable position for Black in Nogueiras Santiago-Ivanchuk,
Havana 2006.}) 11... f6 12. Nf3 (12. Ng4 $5 {has been played in a couple of
games.}) 12... Bb7 13. Qb1 Qd7 14. Re1 (14. e4 $6 Nb6 $1 {helps Black.}) 14...
Re8 (14... Nb6 $2 {runs into} 15. Ng5 $1) 15. h4 (15. e4 Nb6 16. Bh3 c6 17. Bf4
Qf7 18. Nd2 e5 $1 19. dxe5 fxe5 20. Be3 Bc8 21. Bf1 N6d7 22. Qb4 Nf6 23. f3 Qc7
24. Nb1 Be6 {with about equality in Gleichmann-Turkov, ICCF 2013.}) 15... Bc6
16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 18. e4 Nb6 19. h5 Bc6 (19... Na4 20. h6 g6 21. g4
c6 22. g5 Qe7 23. gxf6 Qxf6 24. Ne5 Qe7 25. Qa2 Nd7 26. Nxc4 $16 {Salgado
Allaria-Nechaev, ICCF 2014.}) 20. h6 g6 21. g4 Qd6 22. Qc1 Qd8 23. Bf4 N8d7 24.
g5 $36 {and Black's position looks very unpleasant to play in
Percze-Degerhammar, ICCF 2015.}) (8... Bxc3 {leads to similar play as 8...b5.})
9. e3 N8d7 10. Nxd7 (10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {is unproblematic for Black.}) (
10. f4 $6 O-O 11. O-O c5 $1 {gives Black an easy game in Petkov-Gonzalez
Trigal, Santiago de Compostela 2020.}) 10... Qxd7 11. Ne4 ({This has been
White's main idea. Try to exchange dark-squared bishops and regains the pawn
on c4, claiming an edge thanks to his better light-squared bishop. It's also
possible to start with} 11. O-O {with likely a transposition.}) 11... a5 $1 ({
Other moves are inferior in my opinion, e.g.} 11... Qb5 $6 12. O-O O-O 13. a4
$1 Qa5 14. Qe1 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Qxd2 16. Nxd2 $16 {this is the kind of scenario
Black wishes to avoid. The remainder is quite instructively played by White:}
Bd7 17. a5 Nd5 18. Rfc1 Bb5 19. Bf1 c5 20. dxc5 Rfc8 21. Nxc4 Rxc5 22. Nb6 Rxc1
23. Rxc1 Nxb6 24. axb6 Bc6 25. Bg2 Kf8 26. Bxc6 bxc6 27. Rxc6 Rb8 28. f4 Ke7
29. e4 Kd7 30. Rc7+ Kd8 31. Rxf7 Rxb6 32. Rxg7 Rxb2 33. Rxh7 a5 34. Ra7 Ra2 35.
h4 Ke8 36. h5 Kf8 37. h6 {1-0 Nakamura-Kraai, Saint Louis 2010.}) 12. O-O (12.
a3 Be7 $5 {I like this more than capturing on d2.} 13. Nc5 Qb5 $1 (13... Bxc5
$6 14. dxc5 Nd5 15. Qg4 $6 ({As White's idea backfires he should look for
something else. Perhaps} 15. O-O O-O 16. e4 $5) 15... O-O 16. Qxc4 b6 $1 {
and Black solved the problem of his light-squared bishop in
Baryshpolets-Rambaldi, Charlotte 2019.}) 14. a4 Qxb2 $1 15. Rb1 (15. O-O $2 c3
{and Black's just better.}) 15... Qa3 16. Ra1 Bxc5 $5 ({An interesting attempt
to avoid an immediate repetition with} 16... Qb2 $11) 17. Rxa3 Bxa3 18. Qc2 O-O
19. O-O Bb4 20. Ra1 Bd7 21. Bxb7 (21. Bxb4 axb4 22. a5 b3 23. Qc3 Na4 24. Qxc4
b2 25. Rb1 c5 26. Bxb7 Rxa5 27. Be4 Rb8 $36) 21... Rab8 22. Be4 Bxa4 23. Bxh7+
{and a draw agreed in Sabaev-Rogos, ICCF 2015, in view of} Kh8 24. Qe4 g6 25.
Bxg6 fxg6 26. Qxg6 Bxd2 27. Qh6+ $11) 12... O-O ({The other setup with} 12...
Nd5 13. Qc2 b6 {is very solid as well, e.g.} 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. Rfc1 Bb7 ({
More ambitious is} 15... Ba6 {but the following game shows that Black's
position isn't without any danger:} 16. Nd2 $1 b5 17. Ne4 Bc8 18. Nc5 Qe7 19.
b3 $1 {Provoking Black to make a protected passed in order to dismantle
Black's pawn chain!} c3 20. Qd3 c6 21. e4 Nb6 22. a3 bxa3 23. Qxc3 O-O 24. Qb4
e5 25. d5 Bd7 26. Rxa3 cxd5 27. exd5 Rxa3 28. Qxa3 Rc8 29. b4 {and Black
remained under pressure in Stephan-Lelenko, ICCF 2013 and eventually went on
