18. Qxd2 c5 $11 {Ledford-Holloway, ICCF 2013.}) 15... c6 16. a3 Bxd2 17. Rxd2
e5 $1 18. dxe5 Bf5 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Qxf5 Qxc5 {and Black is fine in Salgado
Allaria-Denisov, ICCF 2018.}) 14... Qb5 $1 15. b3 (15. Nc5 Bxd2 16. Rxd2 Nd5
17. Bf1 b6 18. Bxc4 Qc6 {is fine for Black in Pawlowski-Perini, ICCF 2013.})
15... cxb3 16. axb3 (16. Qxb3 Qa4 17. Qxa4 Nxa4 18. Bxb4 axb4 19. Rdb1 f5 $5
20. Ng5 e5 21. Rxb4 (21. dxe5 c5 $1) 21... exd4 22. exd4 h6 23. Nh3 Nc3 {
with equality in Fischer-Hesse, ICCF 2018.}) 16... Bxd2 17. Nxd2 c6 {White has
some compensation for the pawn, but nothing more. Black is ready to play ...
e6-e5.} 18. Nc4 Qb4 19. Ne5 Bd7 20. Nd3 Qb5 21. Ra3 Nd5 22. Rda1 b6 23. b4 Nxb4
{½-½ Koegler-Iotov, ICCF 2013.}) 8... O-O ({Giving up the dark-squared
bishop is positionally too risky.} 8... Bxc3 $6 9. bxc3 b5 ({After} 9... Nxc3
10. Qc2 {White regains one of the two invested pawns, with ample compensation
for the pawn.}) 10. e4 Ne7 (10... Nxc3 $2 11. Qf3 {wins a piece for White as
seen in Hedman-Prraneeth, Karlsruhe 2019.}) 11. a4 Bb7 12. Ba3 O-O 13. Rb1 c6
14. h4 Nd7 15. Nxc4 $16 {and White regained the pawn in Krasenkova-Sadzikowski,
Wroclaw 2012, retaining a positionally dominant advantage.}) ({The other main
