23. Rc1 Qd2 24. Rc5 Qxa2 25. Qxa5 Bb3 $11 {Miroshnichenko-Kasimdzhanov, Konya
2010.}) 15... O-O (15... b3 $2 {is bad, in view of} 16. Qa3 $1 a5 17. Bxa8 Bb4
18. Qc1 {and Black's queenside collapsed in Halkias-Galopoulos, Plovdiv 2012.})
16. Bxa8 e5 17. Qd5 (17. Qc5 Bh3 18. Qxc4 Bxf1 19. Rxf1 Qe6 20. Qxe6 fxe6 {
and Black should be able to equalize.}) 17... Be6 18. Qd6 Bf5 19. e4 (19. Rbc1
Bg4 20. Rc2 Qf5 21. Rfc1 Bd4 22. e3 b3 23. axb3 cxb3 24. exd4 bxc2 25. dxe5 Be2
{with about an even game in Avrukh-Naiditsch, Sibenik 2012.}) 19... Bh3 20.
Qxf6 gxf6 21. Rfd1 Bg4 22. Rd8 Rxd8 23. Bxd8 Be2 24. Ba5 Nd7 25. Rxb4 (25. Bxb4
Bd3 $1) 25... Kg7 26. Bd5 Bxb4 27. Bxb4 Kg6 28. f4 f5 $11 {Helbich-Lifanov,
ICCF 2014.}) 9. Qc2 {This move, which gained some popularity thanks to a
splendid victory by Kramnik against Morozevich in the World Championship 2007,
