17. c6 Bc8 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 {gives White sufficient compensation for the pawn,
but nothing more in Gelfand-Esipenko, Moscow 2019.}) 12... Bc3 (12... Be7 $6
13. Nec5 Bc6 14. Bb2 Nf6 15. e4 Bxc5 16. Nxc5 Nbd7 17. Nxd7 Nxd7 {was seen in
Harikrishna-Nakamura, Kolkata 2019 and now after} 18. d5 $1 {White seems to
develop a strong initiative for the pawn.}) (12... Nd7 13. Nxb4 Nxb4 {it may
seem a bit strange giving up the dark-squared bishop, which may seem to give
White an edge, but matters aren't that simple, e.g.} 14. Ba3 a5 15. Qd2 c5 16.
Rfc1 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Rc8 {is OK for Black in Ruefenacht-Mahnke, GER email 2015.})
(12... Nc3 {hasn't been tested yet and I don't think it fully equalizes.} 13.
Nxc3 Bxc3 (13... Bxg2 14. Nxb4 Bxf1 15. Kxf1 $16) 14. Bxb7 Ra7 15. Ra2 $5 (15.
Bg2 $6 Bxa1 16. e3 c5 $1 {and White isn't able to trap the bishop.}) 15... Rxb7
16. e3 Qd5 17. Rc2 Ba5 18. Nc5 {followed by 19.e4 with good compensation for
the pawn.}) 13. Bg5 (13. Nxc3 Nxc3 14. Qc2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qxd4 16. Bb2 b4 17.
Bxc3 Qxc3 18. Qxc3 bxc3 19. Rfc1 Nd7 20. Rxc3 c5 $11) 13... Qe8 (13... f6 14.
Rc1 Bxd4 (14... fxg5 $2 15. Ndc5 $1) 15. Ndc5 Bxc5 16. Nxc5 Bc8 17. Bd2 $44 {
and I quite like White's prospects (e2-e4-e5 etc.) despite the two minus pawns.
}) 14. Nxc3 (14. Rc1 Bxd4 15. Ndc5 Bxc5 16. Nxc5 Bc6 17. e4 Nb6 18. Qc2 $6 (18.
Qg4 $5 f5 19. Qe2 $44) 18... h6 19. Be3 a5 {Black untangles in
Kriebel-Esipenko, Prague 2020.}) 14... Nxc3 15. Qc2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qc6+ 17. f3
h6 18. Bd2 Nd5 {and here White has the choice whether to keep queens on the
board or play} (18... Nxe2 $2 19. Qb2 $1 {and the knight is trapped.}) 19. Rfc1
{straightaway. Anyway, after} Ne7 (19... Qb6 20. e4 Ne7 21. Bb4 (21. Qxc7 $2
Qxd4) 21... Nbc6 22. Bc5 $44) 20. Bb4 Qxc2 21. Rxc2 Nbc6 22. Bxe7 Nxe7 23. Rxc7
Nf5 {Black is OK.}) (9. Bd2 Nb6 10. Ne4 Bxd2 11. Qxd2 {was seen in Bareev-Hua,
Kingston 2019 and now} f6 12. Nf3 Nc6 {looks pretty solid for Black.}) 9... b5
$1 (9... Nb6 $6 10. Ne4 $1 Be7 (10... Qxd4 11. Bf4 $1) 11. Rd1 N8d7 12. Nxc4
Nxc4 13. Qxc4 {in case White regains the pawn on c4, Black's position is
generally considered to be inferior. The following game confirms that verdict:}
Nb6 14. Qc2 Nd5 15. Nc5 b6 16. Nd3 Bb7 17. e4 Nf6 18. Ne5 Rc8 19. Bf4 Bd6 20.
Rac1 $14 {Cerrato-Baiocchi, ICCF 2012.}) 10. Nxd5 (10. a4 f6 11. Ng4 Bb7 12.
axb5 Bxc3 13. bxc3 axb5 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Rb1 Qd7 {and Black is OK
in Koegler-Efremov, ICCF 2010.}) (10. Be4 Bb7 11. Nxd5 (11. Bxh7+ Kh8 12. Be4
Nc6 13. Rd1 (13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bg2 Ne7 15. Rd1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 f5 {is
unproblematic for Black in Joppich-Mayer, GER email 2016.}) 13... Nxe5 14. dxe5
{and I believe that Black has a couple of reasonable options here.} f5 (14...
Bxc3 15. bxc3 c5 16. Bg2 f5 17. exf6 Qxf6 18. Rf1 Rab8 19. Bd2 Nb6 $132 {
Helbich-Poleshchuk, ICCF 2013.}) 15. Bg2 Bxc3 16. bxc3 c5 17. e4 fxe4 18. Bxe4
Qc7 19. f4 Ne7 $5 {and White has to be a bit careful in Rawlings-Franke, ICCF
2014.}) 11... Bxd5 12. Bxh7+ Kh8 13. Be4 Bxe4 ({More natural than} 13... Qe8 {
which was played in Gelfand-Morozevich, Biel 2009.}) 14. Qxe4 Qd5 15. Qg4 Nd7
16. Bf4 Nf6 17. Qh4+ Kg8 18. Rad1 a5 {Other moves have been seen here as well
and look playable too.} 19. f3 c3 20. a3 cxb2 21. axb4 a4 22. e4 Qb3 23. Bh6 a3
24. Rd3 b1=Q 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 {½-½ Mendl-Jonsson, ICCF 2014.}) 10... exd5 11. b3
c6 12. e4 ({The main alternative} 12. bxc4 {has been seen here as well, but
after the ambitious reply} dxc4 $1 {it seems to me that Black's queenside
majority is more threatening than White's centre.} 13. Rd1 (13. Nxc6 $6 Nxc6
14. Bxc6 Bh3 {is very comfortable for Black. One example:} 15. Rd1 Rc8 16. Bb7
Rc7 17. Bf3 Re8 18. e4 Bf8 19. Bf4 Rc8 20. e5 a5 21. Bb7 b4 $1 22. d5 c3 23.
Bxc8 Qxc8 {with fantastic compensation for the exchange.} 24. Re1 Qd7 25. Qe4
a4 26. Rac1 Bf5 27. Qd4 Rc8 28. d6 Qb7 29. e6 Bxe6 30. Rxe6 fxe6 31. Bg5 Qd7
32. Qxb4 Bxd6 {and Black went on to convert his extra pawn in Refalo-Mueller,
ICCF 2018.}) 13... Qc7 14. Be4 h6 15. a4 Ra7 16. f4 Bd6 {and Black is
absolutely in control:} 17. Bf3 (17. Rb1 Re8 18. Bf3 Bh3 19. Ng4 Qc8 20. Nf2
Be6 21. e4 f5 $1 {gaining control over the light-squares.} 22. d5 cxd5 23. exd5
Bd7 24. Bb2 Rb7 25. Qc3 Bf8 {and Black is better and went on to win in
Mikheev-Sadowski, ICCF 2012.}) 17... Rd8 18. Bb2 Qe7 19. Kg2 Rc7 20. Rab1 Bb4
21. Ba1 a5 22. e4 {White's centre isn't impressive at all:} Nd7 23. Nxd7 Bxd7
24. f5 Rcc8 25. Rbc1 g6 $1 26. fxg6 fxg6 27. e5 Bf5 28. Qe2 h5 {and Black's
extra pawns on the queenside will eventually tell in Sabaev-Becsenescu, ICCF
2015.}) 12... f6 ({Another option is} 12... Ra7 $5 {which is fine for Black as
well, e.g.} 13. exd5 cxd5 14. bxc4 dxc4 15. Rb1 Bd6 16. a4 f6 17. Nf3 Bd7 18.
d5 Rc7 19. axb5 axb5 20. Nd4 b4 {was seen in Alvarez Villar-Fernandez Medina,
ICCF 2016 and now} 21. Nc6 Nxc6 22. dxc6 Bxc6 23. Qxc4+ Kh8 24. Bxc6 Qc8 25.
Bd2 Rxc6 26. Qb5 $11) 13. exd5 fxe5 14. bxc4 exd4 15. dxc6 Qd6 $1 (15... Be6
16. cxb5 d3 $2 ({In two later games, Black opted for} 16... Ra7 17. Rb1 d3 18.
Qb2 d2 19. Bxd2 Bxd2 20. b6 Raf7 21. Rbd1 Nxc6 22. Rxd2 Rd7 23. Rfd1 Nb8 24. b7
$44 {and the game Richert-Razumichin, ICCF 2010 eventually ended in a draw,
though practically it might be quite annoying that the knight is restricted by
the b-pawn.}) 17. c7 Qd4 $2 ({It would have made more sense to play} 17... Qd6
{right away.}) 18. Qa4 $1 Nd7 19. Be3 Qd6 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 21. Bf4 Qf8 22. b6 {
and White soon won in Kramnik-Morozevich, Mexico City 2007.} Nxb6 $2 {fails to}
23. Qc6 $1) 16. c7 ({Inferior is} 16. cxb5 $6 axb5 17. c7 d3 18. Qb3+ Be6 19.
Bf4 Bxb3 20. Bxd6 Bxd6 21. Bxa8 Bc4 $1 22. cxb8=Q Rxb8 23. Be4 d2 $1 24. Rfd1
Be5 25. Rab1 Bc3 {and in Gmuer-Kolesar, ICCF 2008, White still had to be
careful holding the balance.}) 16... d3 17. Qb3 bxc4 18. Qxc4+ Be6 19. Bf4 Bxc4
20. Bxd6 Bxd6 21. Rac1 Ra7 22. cxb8=Q Bxb8 23. Rxc4 Rd7 24. Rd1 Ba7 25. Rd2
Bxf2+ {leads to a drawn ending and hence a draw was agreed in
Winkler-Nasybullin, ICCF 2007.} *

