{[%evp 0,40,29,33,28,7,7,7,7,-15,-19,-19,36,33,17,17,24,-3,-3,-3,35,-64,-57,
-57,-11,-41,-35,8,12,12,22,40,14,-6,-5,-8,-6,2,7,7,6,1,1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nbd2 b5 ({In my opinion this is
the way to go for Black. Another main option here is} 7... Nxd4 {but then
White gets the kind of typical Catalan compensation for the pawn he's looking
for. It seems White can play for a risk-free advantage:} 8. Nxc4 Nxf3+ (8...
Nc6 9. Qc2 $1 ({in my opinion more promising than} 9. Qxd8+ {which was played
in Li-Lagarde, Sitges 2019.}) 9... Nb4 ({After} 9... Bd6 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. Bg5 {
White can develop nice play for the pawn.}) 10. Qb3 Bc5 11. Bd2 Qe7 12. Nfe5
O-O 13. Na5 Qd6 14. Nec4 Qe7 15. Nxb7 Bxb7 16. Bxb7 Rab8 17. Bg2 $16 {with a
very nice advantage for White in Nett-Singeisen, ICCF 2016.}) 9. Bxf3 Qxd1 (
9... Be7 10. Qc2 $1 O-O 11. Rd1 Qe8 12. Bf4 Nd5 (12... Bd8 {was seen in
Gross-Perina, ICCF 2013 and now I would suggest doubling rooks on the d-file
with} 13. Rd2 $14) 13. Bxc7 $1 Qc6 (13... Nxc7 14. Nb6 $1 {is White's point.})
14. Bb6 $1 ({Less convincing is} 14. Be5 $6 b5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Ne3 Qxc2 17.
Nxc2 f6 {and Black is close to equality in Ju Wenjun-Hou Yifan, Beijing 2013.})
14... Bd7 {and now in Makarian-Jumabayev, Moscow 2020, White could increase
his advantage by means of} 15. b3 Rac8 16. Qb2 $16) 10. Rxd1 Be7 (10... Nd5 11.
e4 Nb6 12. Nxb6 cxb6 13. e5 Bc5 14. Bg5 $1 (14. Be3 Bxe3 15. fxe3 Bd7 16. Rd6
Bc6 $11 {and Black held the ensuing rook ending without any particular
difficulties in Harika-Dzagnidze, Saint Louis 2020.}) 14... Bd7 (14... f6 15.
exf6 gxf6 {was seen in Kovalenko-Kveinys, Riga 2013 and now} 16. Rd8+ $1 Kxd8
17. Bxf6+ {with a winning endgame for White.}) 15. Bxb7 Ra7 16. Bc6 {and now
Black should either play 16...h6 or 16...f6 to avoid an immediate disaster,
but it's not what I'd like to recommend you.}) 11. Na5 (11. Bf4 $6 {is
answered with} Nd5 $1 12. Be5 f6 13. e4 Nb6 (13... fxe5 $5 14. exd5 exd5 15.
Bxd5 c6 16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Nxc8 Rxc8 18. Be6 Rc7 {with compensation for the pawn,
but nothing more for White in Taksrud-Johansen, ICCF 2017.}) 14. Nxb6 cxb6 15.
Bc7 e5 16. Bxb6 {as seen in Lei-Pourkashiyan, Al Ain 2015 and now} Be6 17. Rac1
Kf7 18. Rc7 Rac8 19. Rdc1 (19. Rxb7 $6 Rb8 $1 $15) 19... Rhd8 $11) 11... Bb4 (
11... Nd5 12. e4 Bb4 (12... Nf6 13. Bf4 b6 (13... Bd8 $2 14. Rd2 O-O 15. Rad1
Be7 16. Bxc7 $16 {is just very bad for Black in Li-Batsiashvili, Shaoxing 2019.
}) 14. e5 Nd5 15. Rxd5 $1 exd5 (15... bxa5 $2 16. Rxa5 $16 {Bai-Stremavicius,
chess.com 2019.}) 16. Bxd5 Rb8 17. Nc6 Bb7 18. Nxb8 Bxd5 19. Nxa6 $14) (12...
Nb6 13. Bf4 c6 14. Rd3 Nd7 15. Rad1 e5 16. Be3 Nf6 17. Nc4 (17. Rb3 $5 $14)
17... Be6 18. Nxe5 {and now any move seems reasonable for Black, but not} Bxa2
$2 19. b3 O-O 20. Ra1 {1-0 Rombaldoni,A-Caprio, Torino 2012.}) (12... Nb4 {
has never been tried and after} 13. Bf4 $1 {White retains serious pressure, e.
g.} b6 14. Nc4 (14. a3 $5) 14... Ra7 (14... b5 15. Na5 c5 16. a3 Nc2 17. e5
Nxa1 18. Bc6+ $1 Kf8 19. Bxa8 Nc2 20. Nc6 $16) 15. a3 Nc6 16. Rac1 Bd7 17. b4
$36) 13. Nc4 (13. exd5 $5) 13... Nb6 14. Nxb6 cxb6 15. e5 Bc5 16. Bg5 {
transposes to 10...Nd5.}) 12. Bd2 (12. Nxb7 Nd5 13. a3 Bxb7 14. axb4 O-O-O {
looks OK for Black.}) 12... Bxd2 13. Rxd2 Nd5 14. Rad1 O-O 15. a3 b6 16. Nc6
Re8 17. e4 Nf6 18. e5 Nd5 19. Rc1 Bb7 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Rxd5 {and although
managed to hold the endgame in Babychuk-Heide, ICCF 2018, it's certainly not
what you like to have in your repertoire with Black.}) 8. b3 ({The critical
test. White could win the exchange by means of} 8. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 9. Bxa8 (9. dxe5
Nd5 {favors Black.}) 9... Qxd4 10. Ne4 (10. a4 Qb6 (10... Qa7 $2 {should be
met by} 11. Bh1 $3 ({The more logical move} 11. Bg2 $2 Bb7 12. axb5 Bxg2 13.
Qa4 (13. Kxg2 Qb7+ {followed by ...axb5 is better for Black.}) 13... Qa8 $1 14.
Qxa6 Qxa6 15. bxa6 Ba8 $19 {and White's pawn isn't dangerous at all in Hou
Yifan-Negi, Saint Louis 2015.}) 11... Bb7 12. axb5 Bxh1 {and since the rook on
f1 isn't hanging, White can play} 13. Qa4 $1 {threatening to qin the queen
with the discovery b5-b6,} Qb8 (13... Qa8 14. f3 {and the bishop is trapped.})
14. Kxh1 axb5 15. Qa8 {and White is better.}) 11. Nf3 Ned7 12. axb5 axb5 13.
Qd2 (13. Bd2 Bd6 14. Ba5 {was seen in Jijon-Ballow, ICCF 2011 and now the
following sequence looks quite natural to me:} Qb8 15. Bc6 O-O 16. b3 Bb7 17.
Bxd7 Nxd7 18. bxc4 Bxf3 19. exf3 b4 {with about an even game. The bishop on a5
is trapped, but not easy to catch. Must be some sort of dynamical balance.}) (
13. Be3 Bc5 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. Qd4 O-O {and I would prefer to be Black, though
objectively speaking still quite balanced.}) 13... Bc5 14. Qa5 O-O {and with
two pawn for the exchange Black is doing fine in Schoen-Jandek, ICCF 2011.})
10... Qxd1 (10... Qa7 $5 {also comes into consideration.} 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12.
Bg2 h5 $5 {White should act quickly, aiming for the exchange of queens, in
order to avoid being overwhelmed by Black's ambitions on the kingside attack.}
13. Be3 (13. h4 Bc5 {and next the knight jumps to g4.}) 13... Bc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5
15. Qd2 h4 16. Rfd1 Ke7 {Objectively it should be about equal still, but in a
practical game I would rather be Black. The potential passed pawn on the
queenside is causing White some problems to deal with, while i don't see an
active plan activating the rooks.} 17. Qd4 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 hxg3 19. hxg3 Rg8 20.
Rdd1 a5 21. Rac1 Ba6 {and only Black can play for an advantage. The following
game nicely illustrates Black's long-term pressure on the queenside:} 22. f4
Nd7 23. Kf2 c5 24. Rd2 b4 25. a4 Nb6 26. Rcd1 Bc8 27. Bc6 f5 28. Bb5 c3 29.
bxc3 bxc3 30. Rc2 Nd5 31. Rb1 Bd7 32. Bxd7 Kxd7 33. Rb7+ Kc6 34. Rxf7 Rb8 35.
Ra7 Nf6 36. Ke3 Nd5+ 37. Kf2 Rb2 38. Rc1 Kb6 39. Ra8 Rb4 40. Re8 Re4 41. Kf3
Kc7 42. Ra8 Rxa4 43. Ra6 Re4 44. Rxa5 Rc4 45. Ra6 Nb6 46. Ke3 Kb7 47. Ra5 Nd5+
48. Kf3 c2 49. Kf2 Kb6 50. Ra2 Nb4 51. Ra3 Rd4 52. Rb3 Ka5 53. Ra1+ Kb5 54. Ke1
c4 55. Rba3 Rd7 56. Ra5+ Kb6 57. R5a3 Kc5 58. Rc1 Rd8 59. Rca1 Rh8 60. Kd2 Kd4
61. e3+ Ke4 62. Kc3 Nd5+ 63. Kxc2 Rh2+ {0-1 Williamson-Tofan, ICCF 2016.}) 11.
Rxd1 (11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Rxd1 Bc5 $44 {is more than OK for Black in Socko,
B-Gavrilescu, Graz 2020.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bd6 13. Bd2 Ke7 14. Rac1 h5 15.
h4 f6 {is about even in Schwenteck-Jonsson, ICCF 2015.}) 8... c3 ({I think
this principled move equalizes, but in case people are looking for a more
adventurous approach I would suggest having a look at} 8... Rb8 9. Bb2 $1 (9.
bxc4 $6 Nxd4 {has been Black's idea.}) 9... cxb3 (9... c3 $2 {doesn't make
much sense, after} 10. Bxc3 Ba3 {Harika-Kosteniuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2018 White
retains a big positional advantage after something like} 11. Qc2 $16) 10. Nxb3
Be7 (10... Bb7 11. Qc1 Bd6 12. e4 (12. Rd1 Ne7 13. Nc5 O-O (13... Bc6 $5 14.
Nxa6 Rb6 15. Nc5 Qa8 {might be an option too.}) 14. Nxb7 Rxb7 15. a4 Qc8 16.
Qc2 bxa4 17. Ne1 {and although Black is doing reasonable well in
Joppich-Scheiba, ICCF 2015, I'm not convinced it's much playing this kind of
positions OTB.}) 12... Be7 $2 (12... Nxe4 $1 13. Nfd2 f5 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Bxe4
Na5 $1 {is still OK for Black.}) 13. Rd1 O-O {was seen in Lenderman-Ali
Marandi, Charlotte 2020 and now} 14. d5 $1 {looks incredibly strong for White.}
) (10... Bd6 $2 {allows} 11. e4 $1 {as} Nxe4 $2 {fails to} 12. Qc2 {winning a
piece.}) 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. Ne1 ({After} 12. e4 $5 $146 Nxe4 (12... O-O {might be
wiser.}) 13. d5 exd5 14. Ne5 {the position explodes.}) 12... Na7 13. Bxb7 Rxb7
14. Nd3 (14. Qc2 Qa8 15. f3 O-O 16. Nd3 Rc8 17. e4 Nd7 $132 {
Joppich-Baranowski, ICCF 2010.}) 14... O-O 15. Qc2 Qa8 16. Na5 Rb6 17. Qxc7 Nd5
18. Qc2 {with an interesting struggle in Vidit-Nakamura, Kolkata 2019, where
anything can still happen.} Nb4 19. Nxb4 Bxb4 20. Nb3 Rd8) 9. Nb1 b4 10. a3 ({
The principled continuation. After} 10. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 11. Bxa8 Ned7 12. a3 a5 13.
axb4 axb4 14. Qd3 Be7 {Black is fine in Marquardt-Vekelis, ICCF 2015, as the
only way to untangle is sacrificing the knight on c3.}) 10... Rb8 ({This looks
more reliable to me than} 10... Bb7 {and now I think it's more accurate to
start with} 11. Ne5 (11. axb4 Bxb4 (11... Ne4 $5 {, protecting the pawn on c3
and intending to take on b4 with the knight, looks like an equalizer, e.g.} 12.
Ne5 Qxd4 13. Nxc6 (13. Qxd4 $6 Nxd4 14. Nxc3 Nxc3 15. Bxb7 Rb8 {might even
favor Black.}) 13... Qxd1 14. Rxd1 c2 $1 15. Rd4 cxb1=Q 16. Rxb1 Bxc6 17. Bxe4
Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Bd6 $11) 12. Ne5 Nd5 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Qc2 O-O (14... f5 $5 15.
Bb2 cxb2 16. Qxc6+ Kf7 17. Ra2 Qd6 {might be holdable for Black.}) 15. e4 Nf6
16. Rd1 h6 {was seen in Vidit-L'Ami, Batumi 2018 and now I would recommend} 17.
Ba3 a5 18. Nxc3 $14 {with a pleasant edge for White.}) 11... Nd5 $1 {likely
transposes to 11.axb4 after} (11... c2 $6 12. Bxc6+ $1 Bxc6 13. Qxc2 {I don't
see a clear path to equality.}) 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. axb4 Bxb4 {with a
transposition to Vidit-L'Ami.}) 11. axb4 Bxb4 12. Qd3 (12. Ba3 $6 a5 $1) 12...
e5 $1 ({More precise than} 12... O-O 13. Nxc3 e5 {and now I think White should
try} 14. Be3 $5 {with still some chances to play for an advantage, because of
Black's fragmented pawn structure on the queenside.} (14. d5 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qxd5
16. Nd2 Nd4 17. Qxc7 Nxe2+ 18. Kh1 Qb5 {which was fine for Black in
Harika-Kosteniuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2018.})) 13. Nxc3 ({Two days before this
game in the same event, one game went} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qxd3 15. exd3 Nd7
16. d4 O-O 17. Be3 c5 18. Rc1 cxd4 19. Bxd4 Nc5 20. Bxc5 Bxc5 21. Nxc3 Bd4 {
with a very drawish position in Kobo-Melkumyan, Sitges 2019.}) (13. d5 $2 {
fails to} e4 $1 $19) 13... exd4 14. Ne4 O-O 15. Bb2 Bf5 16. Nxd4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4
Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Re8 20. Qg4 Bf8 $11 {with a very even game in
Bjerre-Donchenko, Sitges 2019.} *

