{[%evp 0,44,27,25,32,6,6,6,6,-10,-10,-10,23,31,38,2,-5,-5,45,25,20,13,0,0,7,0,
22,22,4,0,0,26,29,37,30,30,30,33,52,36,32,36,33,33,39,26,20]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. O-O Nc6 7. Bg5 ({White is trying to get
an more active version of the Main Lines with} 7. e3 {(Chapter 8-11), by
developing his dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.}) 7... Be7 ({
The easiest way to neutralize White's setup. The main alternatives} 7... Rb8 {
and}) (7... h6 {are less convincing.}) 8. e3 O-O ({Simple and theoretically
speaking Black's best attempt. The alternatives} 8... Bd7 {and}) (8... Nd5 {
don't fully equalize.}) 9. Nbd2 (9. Nfd2 e5 $1 10. Bxf6 ({In case of} 10. Bxc6
{two straight intermediate moves ensure equality for Black:} c3 $5 ({More
precise than} 10... bxc6 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxc4 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5
15. Nc3 $14) 11. Nxc3 exd4 {and Black equalizes.}) 10... Bxf6 11. d5 Na5 $1 (
11... Ne7 $6 12. Nc3 c6 13. dxc6 Nxc6 14. Nxc4 Be6 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 $14 {
Pulvett Marin-Gonzalez Trigal, Pontevedra 2019.}) 12. Qa4 (12. b4 {as played
in Lalith-Sebenik, chess.com 2018 can just be met by} e4 $1) 12... c6 $1 13.
dxc6 b5 14. Qc2 {was played in Mareco-Carlsson, Caleta 2015 and now} Be6 $1 {
favors Black, in view of} 15. c7 Qxc7 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 {with fantastic
compensation for the exchange.}) (9. Qe2 h6 (9... Na5 10. Nfd2 {was seen in
Heinsohn-Schumacher, ICCF 2018 and now} Bd7 $5 {intending ...c7-c5 looks OK
for Black.}) 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Rd1 (11. Qxc4 $6 {allows} e5 $1 12. dxe5 Nxe5
13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nc3 c6 $15 {Batsiashvili-Koneru, Batumi 2012.}) 11... Na5 12.
Nfd2 {was seen in Lenderman-Azarov, Dayton 2016 and here I would consider} Bd7
13. Nxc4 c5 {and White isn't able exploiting tactically the d-file, e.g.} 14.
dxc5 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Bxb2 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. c6 Bxa1 18. Rxd7 Qxd7 19. cxd7 Rxb7
$11) 9... e5 $1 ({The key move which neutralizes White's concept. Inferior is} 
9... Na5 $6 {in view of} 10. Ne5 $1 c5 11. Ndxc4 Nxc4 12. Nxc4 cxd4 13. Qxd4
Qxd4 14. exd4 {and thanks to the Catalan bishop on g2 White retains long-term
pressure, e.g.} Nd5 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Rac1 Rb8 17. Nb6 Rd8 18. Rc7 Nd5 19. Bxd5
exd5 20. a4 $16 {Postny-Melaa, Kragero 2020.}) 10. Nxc4 ({The main alternative
is} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxc4 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 (14. Qd4
Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Be6 16. Qc3 c6 $11 {Xiong-Cornette, chess.com 2018.}) 14... Qxe5
15. Qd4 (15. Qb3 c6 16. Rfd1 (16. f4 Qb5 17. Qc3 Rd8 18. a4 Qh5 19. Rf2 Bh3 {
and Black solved his opening problems in Cadenas Gonzalez-Quidiello Prado,
ICCF 2017.}) 16... Qc7 (16... Qb5 $6 17. Qc3 Be6 18. a4 $1 Qh5 19. Qb4 Rab8 20.
Qb6 {is exactly the kind of scenario Black should try to avoid, as Black isn't
able to control the d-file. White is pressing and gradually increases the
pressure on all sides of the board. The following game is quite instructive:}
h6 21. Rd6 Bg4 22. a5 Rfe8 23. b4 Qe5 24. Rd4 h5 25. h3 Bf5 26. Rc1 Qe6 27. h4
Bg4 28. Rc2 Qb3 29. Rcd2 Qc3 30. Kh2 g6 31. e4 Rec8 32. Rd6 Kg7 33. Qc5 Qxc5
34. bxc5 Kf8 35. f4 Ke7 36. Bh3 Bxh3 37. Kxh3 {with a winning rook ending for
White in Shirov-Oparin, Moscow 2016.}) 17. Qc3 Be6 18. a4 a5 $1 {A good move,
not allowing White fixing the queenside like Shirov was allowed to do after 16.
..Qb5?!.} 19. Bf3 (19. Bd5 Rad8 20. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 {and White isn't able to
exploit the weak pawn on e6. Marquardt-Novikov, ICCF 2018.}) 19... Rad8 20. b4
Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 axb4 22. Qxb4 g6 23. Rb1 Bc8 $11 {Figlio-Hernandez Molina, ICCF
2018.}) 15... Qe7 (15... Qxd4 16. exd4 c6 17. d5 cxd5 18. Bxd5 Rd8 19. Rfd1 Kf8
20. Rac1 Rb8 21. f3 Be6 22. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 {Eljanov-Duda, Doha 2014.}) 16. Rfd1
c6 17. Qc3 Be6 18. a3 Rfd8 $11 {Lalith-Adams, Caleta 2020.}) (10. dxe5 {
is likely to lead to the same position.}) 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 ({Exchanging one
pair of knight in order to open the diagonal for the bishop on g2.} 11. exd4 h6
{is fine for Black.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 (12. exd4 {shouldn't be problematic
for Black, e.g.} h6 13. Bf4 Nd5 14. Bd2 Be6 15. Re1 Re8 {with a very solid
position, but not} (15... Rc8 $2 {which ran into} 16. Rxe6 $1 {which gave
White a spectacular win:} fxe6 17. Bh3 Rf6 18. Qe2 Rb8 19. Bxe6+ Kf8 20. Qg4
Bb4 21. Bxb4+ Nxb4 22. Ne5 h5 23. Qxh5 Ke7 24. d5 Nxd5 25. Bxd5 Qxd5 26. Ng6+ {
1-0 Gormally-Sowray, Daventry 2020.})) 12... Qxd4 ({This would be my choice,
but also playable is} 12... Be6 13. Na5 h6 14. Bxf6 (14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Bf4 Nd5
{with equality in Gleizerov-Vaibhav, Visakhapatnam 2011, as the pawn on b2 is
as weak as the one on b7.}) 14... Bxf6 15. Qe4 {and now either 15...c6 or 15...
Qd2 suffices, as soon the pawns on the queenside will be liquidated.} (15. Qxd8
Raxd8 16. Nxb7 Rd2 17. Nc5 Bxb2 18. Rad1 Rfd8 $11 {Fischer-Lelgemann, GER
email 2016.})) 13. exd4 h6 $1 ({Questioning the bishop on g5 is correct, as
Black shouldn't take matters too lightly, e.g.} 13... Rd8 $6 14. Rfd1 $1 ({
More precise than} 14. Rad1 Bg4 15. Rc1 (15. Rde1 Bb4 16. Rc1 Be2 $1 {reveals
the difference!}) 15... c6 16. Nb6 Rab8 17. Bf4 Bd6 {which was OK for Black in
Moradiabadi-Nielsen, Peristeri 2010.}) 14... Bg4 15. Re1 Bb4 16. Rec1 Rab8 (
16... c6 {is met by} 17. d5 $1 cxd5 18. Nb6 Rab8 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Nxd5 {
and a loss of material can't be avoided.}) 17. a3 Bf8 18. Ne3 Rxd4 19. Rxc7 {
with an overwhelming advantage for White in Ponomariov-Morozevich, Moscow 2009.
}) (13... Be6 $2 {allows} 14. Na5 $1 {and Black will suffer.}) 14. Bf4 (14. Bd2
Be6 15. Na5 Bd5 16. Rfe1 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rfe8 18. Nxb7 Rab8 19. Na5 Rxb2 20. Nc4
Rc2 21. Rec1 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 c5 $11 {Mrkvicka-Babic, ICCF 2017.}) (14. Rfe1 Be6
15. d5 Nxd5 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Na5 (17. Bxb7 Ra7 $1) 17... c6 18. Nxb7 Rab8 19.
Nc5 Rxb2 $11) 14... Be6 $1 15. Rfe1 (15. Na5 Nd5 $1 {This is the point to have
the moves 13...h6 14.Bf4 inserted.} 16. Bd2 $6 Bf6 17. Rad1 Rab8 $15 {
Mis-Hrbek, Prague 2020.}) 15... Bxc4 (15... c6 16. Na5 Bb4 17. Rxe6 fxe6 18.
Nxb7 Nd5 19. Be5 {gave White reasonable compensation for the exchange in
Yuffa-Oparin, Sochi 2018.}) 16. Rxe7 Nd5 17. Bxd5 Bxd5 18. Rxc7 Rac8 {and
White's extra pawn isn't worth much:} 19. Rc5 Rfd8 20. b3 Rxc5 21. dxc5 Bf3 22.
Re1 Rd5 {½-½ Yuffa-Potkin, Sochi 2019.} *

