{[%evp 0,70,25,20,24,20,20,20,20,-11,-11,-17,30,30,29,-5,18,9,12,-10,-10,9,3,
76,28,37,55,12,12,14,29,14,54,24,24,24,24,24,24,6,24,20,26,21,29,25,25,11,48,
-54,-45,-47,-47,-33,-53,-48,-40,-32,-19,-19,-2,-12,-12,-12,-12,-10,-10,-10,-10,
-10,-10,-10,-8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. O-O Nc6
7. Nc3 {This is the second-most popular move, as White proceeds in gambit
style, ignoring the pawn on c4. Interesting for those who are looking for
sharp play, but Black players don't have to be worried when they know their
stuff!} Rb8 $1 ({An important move, as the automatic} 7... Be7 $6 {enables
White regaining the pawn with} 8. Qa4 $1 $16) 8. e4 Be7 ({The most sensible
continuation. About 10-15 years ago the move} 8... b5 $6 {had been seen in
several GM games, but ever since disappeared from the tournament arena and for
a good reason:} 9. d5 $1 Nb4 ({A better attempt is} 9... exd5 10. exd5 Nb4 11.
b3 (11. Nd4 $2 Bd7 $1 12. Re1+ Be7 13. Qe2 Nd3 14. Bg5 Kf8 $1 {and Black is
winning in Landa-Naiditsch, Mainz 2009.}) 11... Bd6 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. Qe2+ Qe7
14. Qxc4 O-O 15. Bg5 (15. a3 Nc2 $1 16. Ra2 Nxa3 {is OK for Black.}) 15... a5
16. Rfe1 Qd8 {and optically White is better, but since ...Ba6 is coming next
Black is OK and all correspondence games have ended in a draw.}) 10. b3 $1 (10.
Ne5 $6 {is met by} Bd6 $1 11. f4 exd5 12. a3 Nd3 13. Nxd3 (13. Nc6 $2 {loses to
} Bc5+ 14. Kh1 Qd6 15. Nxb8 $2 Ng4 $1 {and Black is winning (threats on f2 and
h2).}) 13... cxd3 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 O-O 16. Qxd3 Qf6 $15 {and Black is
better in Barbosa-Kasimdzhanov, Mashhad 2011.}) 10... cxb3 (10... exd5 11. exd5
Bd6 {see 9...exd5.}) 11. Qxb3 c5 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. Bf4 Rb7 {This position came
into the spotlights after the game Nielsen-Van Wely, Dortmund 2005. The Danish
theoretician opted for 14.e5, but nowadays in correspondence play White
players are merciless! Some examples:} 14. Rfd1 (14. Rac1 Na5 15. Qc2 Ba3 16.
e5 Nh5 (16... Nd7 17. Bg5 f6 18. exf6 gxf6 19. Nd4 $1 Rb6 20. Rce1 O-O 21. Nxe6
Rxe6 22. Rxe6 Nc4 (22... fxg5 23. Rh6 {is crushing.}) 23. Bh6 Nce5 24. Bxf8
Qxf8 25. Nd5 {1-0 Ortiz-Dziedzina, LSS email 2010.}) 17. Bg5 f6 18. exf6 gxf6
19. Rcd1 Rd7 20. Bh6 Kf7 21. g4 Ng7 22. Rxd7+ Qxd7 23. Ne4 Nc4 24. Nxf6 $1 {
Dimitrios-Tyshkun, ICCF 2019:} Kxf6 25. Qc3+ e5 (25... Kg6 26. Nh4+ Kxh6 27.
Qf6#) 26. Nxe5 Nxe5 27. f4 {and White wins.}) 14... Rd7 15. e5 Na5 16. Qc2
Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Nd7 18. Ng5 Nc4 19. a4 Qb6 20. Nd5 $1 Qb8 (20... exd5 21. Bxd5 {
with a devastating attack.}) 21. Ne3 h6 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Qg6+ Ke7 24. Nxc4
bxc4 25. Bf3 $3 {A wonderful silent move.} Qa7 26. Bg4 c3 27. Qxe6+ {1-0
Fenes-Zalcik, ICCF 2010. After seeing these illustrative games I don't think
there is anyone in the world eager repairing the variation with 8...b5?!,
though 9...exd5 seems to be playable still.}) 9. Qe2 ({The sharpest move. The
immediate break in the centre} 9. d5 {doesn't promise White anything:} exd5 (
9... Nb4 {likely transposes.}) 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne5 Bf5 (11... Nd3 12. Nxd3
cxd3 13. Qxd3 $14 {and compared with the main line Black can't easily develop
the queen's bishop.}) 12. a3 Nd3 13. Nxc4 {and now both} Nxc1 {and} (13... O-O
{are leading to equal positions.})) 9... b5 $5 ({This has mainly been played,
but I think grabbing a second pawn is certainly possible too.} 9... Nxd4 10.
Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 {This is considered to be the best square for the queen,
guarding the e5-square.} 12. e5 (12. Be3 Qa5 13. Qxc4 (13. Bd2 Qh5 14. Bf3 Qc5
(14... Qh3 $4 15. e5 Nd7 16. Bg4 {and the queen is trapped.}) 15. Be3 Qa5 16.
Bd2 Qc5 $11) 13... e5 {is fine for Black, e.g.} 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Be6 16.
Rxa5 Bxc4 17. Rxe5 Be6 $15 {and I would slightly prefer to be Black in
Ivanisevic-Milov, Cannes 2006.}) 12... Nd7 (12... Nd5 $2 {has been seen in
here as well, including some games of very strong GMs. Modern engines scream
out loud} 13. Rxd5 $1 exd5 14. Nxd5 {and White is clearly better, likely soon
to regain the invested material with great interest.}) 13. Ne4 Qb5 $1 (13...
Qxe5 $2 {can't be recommended, in view of} 14. Bf4 Qa5 15. Qxc4 e5 16. Bg5 $1 {
and despite the two minus pawns, White is clearly better.}) 14. a4 (14. Bf4 O-O
15. Rac1 c3 $1 ({More accurate than} 15... Nb6 16. Qg4 Nd7 {in view of} 17. a4
$5 (17. Qe2 {is a repetition.}) 17... Qxb2 (17... Qxa4 $2 18. Bh6 {and Black
can't take on e5 with the queen,}) 18. Rb1 f5 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Rxb2 Nxg4 21.
Bxc7 Ra8 22. a5 {and though the position in Pavoni-Silva, ICCF 2010, is close
to equal, I would slightly prefer to be White.}) 16. Qxb5 axb5 17. Rxc3 c6 18.
Rcd3 Nc5 ({More ambitious is} 18... Nb6 $5 19. Nf6+ gxf6 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. Bxb8
Nc4 {with sufficient compensation for the exchange in Godat-Wurschner, LSS
email 2009.}) 19. Nxc5 Bxc5 20. Be3 Be7 {with compensation for the pawn, but
nothing more, e.g.} 21. a3 Ra8 22. b4 f6 23. f4 Kf7 24. h4 g6 25. Be4 Kg7 26.
Kg2 f5 27. Bf3 {½-½ Beecham-Galanov, ICCF 2010.}) 14... Qa5 ({More
convincing than} 14... Qb3 $6 15. Bd2 b5 16. Qg4 {which I wouldn't really
enjoy playing with Black, being forced to play} Kf8) 15. Bd2 (15. Qxc4 Nxe5 16.
Qd4 O-O 17. Bd2 Qd5 18. Qe3 Qd8 {gives White some play, but don't forget it's
a two pawn difference and Black can always give back some material. I don't
see any problems for Black:} 19. Qc3 (19. Bc3 Nd7 $1) 19... Bd6 20. Be3 Qe7 21.
Nxd6 cxd6 22. Bb6 Nc6 23. b4 e5 24. b5 axb5 {½-½ Kappes-Botev, ICCF 2013} 25.
axb5 Nd4 26. Bxd4 exd4 27. Rxd4 Be6 $11) 15... Bb4 16. Qxc4 (16. Bxb4 Qxb4 17.
Qg4 Qxb2 18. Qxg7 Qxe5 19. Qh6 b6 20. Rac1 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rxd7 {½-½
Rogetzer-Galanov, ICCF 2011} Kxd7 23. Rd1+ Ke7 24. Qh4+ f6 25. Qh6 Rf8 26. Qg7+
Rf7 27. Qg8 Rf8 28. Qg7+ Rf7 {with a repetition.}) 16... Bxd2 17. Rxd2 b5 18.
Qc2 (18. Qc6 O-O 19. f4 (19. Rxd7 Bxd7 20. Qxd7 Rfd8 21. Qc6 bxa4 {is fine for
Black too.}) 19... bxa4 20. Rxa4 Qb6+ 21. Qxb6 Nxb6 22. Ra2 Bb7 23. Nc5 $11 {
Umansky-Bernhaupt, Chessfriend.com 2004.}) 18... O-O ({Also possible is} 18...
