well-coordinated, his position doesn't contain any serious weaknesses and
after all, he is still a pawn up. However, Black shouldn't take matters too
lightly. I think the most sensible continuation is} (17. Qe3 c6 (17... Ra8 $5 {
right away comes into consideration as well.}) 18. h4 {and now in
Tica-Rambaldi, chess.com 2020, Black played 18...Qb6, but after 19.Nc5, take
and dxc5 the queen comes under attack. Hence, I believe the queen isn't so
well placed here. In my opinion, more to the point is} Ra8 {intending to push
the a-pawn and generate counterplay. Black's chances should be preferred.})
17... Ra8 $5 $15 {preparing the queen maneuver via b8 to b7, push the a-pawn,
etc. It seems to me that White isn't that fast generating a kingside attack.
Of course, the position is still full of play, but Black players shouldn't
fear to be a pawn up! :)} *

