{[%evp 0,40,41,14,30,0,0,-3,0,-24,-24,-24,27,34,44,3,16,33,48,48,48,48,48,48,
48,48,48,56,70,62,49,48,68,11,-10,12,12,34,77,23,28,58,34]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. O-O Nc6 7. e3 Rb8 8. Nfd2 e5 9. Bxc6+ bxc6
10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Nxc4 Be6 12. Nbd2 Bb4 {[#] We have reached the main tabiya of
the Open Catalan with 5...a6. The position is incredibly tense and one bad
move is likely to be decisive. Black's last move is a very important
developing move. The key idea is that White isn't able to kick away the knight
on g4 with one his pawns, as it runs into ...Bxd2! Hence, White is recommended
to overprotect the knight on c4 with the queen or b-pawn in order to complete
development and consolidate his structural advantage. Of course, if Black
doesn't act immediately his position is likely to collapse quickly. What
follows is an incredible fight, where from a theoretical point of view I
believe Black's doing alright!} 13. b3 (13. Qe2 {a very natural and safe move.
White overprotects the knight on c4, keeps an eye on the knight on g4 and
keeps the queen close to the kingside. However, Black has a very concrete idea
which neutralizes White's attempt to stabilize his position.} Bxd2 $1 (13... h5
14. b3 {is a transposition to the Main Line with 13.b3.} (14. f3 Bxd2 (14... h4
$2 {is refuted by means of} 15. fxg4 hxg3 16. hxg3 Bxd2 17. Nxd2 Qd5 18. e4
Qxe5 19. Kg2 Qg5 20. Rf5 $1 {and Black doesn't have any counterplay in
Karthikeyan-Van Cappellen, Leer 2018.}) 15. Bxd2 h4 {see 13...Bxd2.})) ({
In the case of} 13... Qd5 $2 {White just protects his pawn on e5 with} 14. f4
$1 {and Black is left without counterplay:} Qb5 15. a4 Qc5 16. b3 h5 17. h3 Nh6
18. Ne4 Qa7 19. Ng5 {and White is completely winning in Ivanchuk-Wemmers,
Caleta 2020.}) 14. Bxd2 (14. Nxd2 Nxe5 {isn't problematic at all for Black.}) (
14. Rd1 {is best met by} Qd5 $1 15. b3 Bxc1 16. Rxd5 cxd5 17. Rxc1 dxc4 {
and only Black could be better here.}) 14... h5 ({Threatening to take on c4,
as the immediate} 14... Bxc4 $2 15. Qxc4 Qxd2 (15... Nxe5 16. Qf4 {followed by
17.Bc3.}) 16. Qxg4 {is just horrible for Black.}) 15. f3 ({White needs to act,
as} 15. Rad1 $2 h4 16. Be1 {is too slow and too passive. Now strong is} Qg5 $1
(16... Qe7 17. Rd4 $2 ({After} 17. f4 $1 Nxh2 18. Qxh2 Bxc4 19. Rf2 {matters
aren't that clear yet.}) 17... Nxh2 $1 {A cool tactical shot!} 18. Kxh2 hxg3+
19. Kg2 (19. Kg1 g2 $1 {and White is forced to remove the g-pawn.}) 19... Rh2+
20. Kf3 (20. Kxg3 Rh3+ 21. Kg2 Qg5+ {and mate follows.}) 20... Qg5 {0-1
Song-Santos Latasa, Caleta 2020.}) 17. f4 Qg6 {and White's position is just
falling apart, as there are simply too many tactical problems he needs to
reckon with. For example:} 18. h3 hxg3 $1 19. hxg4 Bxg4 20. Rf3 (20. Qd3 Rh1+
$1 21. Kg2 Bh3+ 22. Kxh1 g2+ {and Black wins.}) 20... Rh1+ 21. Kxh1 Qh5+ 22.
Kg1 Bxf3 {and Black wins.}) (15. h3 $6 h4 16. hxg4 hxg3 17. fxg3 {see the 15.
f3 when White plays 17.hxg3?!.}) 15... h4 $1 ({More convincing than
simplifying immediately with} 15... Bxc4 $6 16. Qxc4 Qxd2 {Black is close to
equality, but} 17. fxg4 $1 {might still pose some practical problems.} ({After
} 17. Qxc6+ Kf8 18. fxg4 Rxb2 {White has nothing better, but to force a draw
with} 19. Rxf7+ $1 Kxf7 20. Rf1+ Kg8 21. Qe6+ Kh7 22. Qf5+ Kg8 $11)) 16. fxg4
hxg3 {[#]} 17. b3 (17. hxg3 $6 Qd5 $1 18. Rf3 ({Worse is} 18. e4 $6 Qxc4 19.
Qxc4 Bxc4 20. Rfb1 Bd3 21. Rd1 Bxe4 {and White will be suffering in the
endgame as in Batchuluun-Sethuraman, Tianjin 2020.}) 18... Qxc4 19. Qxc4 Bxc4 {
and although managed to win in Deac-Shankland, Douglas 2019, it's clear that
Black is better.}) (17. Rac1 Rxh2 (17... Qh4 18. e4 Bxc4 (18... Bxg4 $2 19. Qg2
$16) 19. Rxc4 Rxb2 20. Rd1 Qxh2+ 21. Qxh2 Rxh2 22. Be1 Rbg2+ 23. Kf1 Rxa2 24.
Kg1 {and neither side avoid the repetition.}) 18. Qf3 Rxd2 (18... g2 19. Qxc6+
